		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform2" ><span class="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=1286"><span id="Sage">gbaji</span></a><b><span id="Sage"><br>Encyclopedia</span></b><br /><span style="font-size:9px;color: red;">There is no 5th star.</span><br />10511 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span class="notbold">Score</span>: Good [4.02]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=gbaji&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%">
<p><blockquote><b class="sm">Quote:</b><hr size="1" />if the general reaction to seeing someone saying paladin spells decreased in power is asking how they decreased, then paladin balance would be in pretty good hands.<hr size="1" /></blockquote> <br /> <br />Eh? By what basis? <br /> <br />If I state that paladin stuns have been reduced in power over time, and no one believes it or takes any action to counterbalance that reduction in power, then exactly how does that put paladin balance &quot;in good hands&quot;? <br /> <br />The problem is that no one asks how they were decreased in a &quot;Gee. Show me what the problem is and we'll look at a way to fix it&quot;. They ask the question in a &quot;what the hell are you talking about!&quot; manner. That clearly shows that they're not looking at ways to address the balance issue created, but are refusing to accept that it exists in the first place. <br /> <br />Judging by your response on this topic, that's exactly how you are approaching the issue as well. Heck. You simplistically ask if we still have enough to chain stun a level 70 mob. That's pretty clear that you don't understand the problems (even though I went over all of this in detail like 3 weeks ago in another thread that you were involved in). <br /> <br /> <br />A level 70 paladin, without spending AAs or getting a lucky award for his &quot;ancient&quot; line will have 2 stuns available to him. That's most certainly not enough to chain stun any mob. One of those spells is a knockback/damage stun. Those are generally not liked since they can cause all sorts of position problems (they also have long recast times, and can't be used for chaining). That spell line is used for repositioning of mobs and &quot;emergency&quot; stunning. They can't be used for stun chains. <br /> <br /> <br /> <br />In order to chain stun a mob, a paladin must have 3 stun spells *not* of the serentity line (the knockback ones). A basic paladin will have 1 of those at level 70. A basic paladin will have 4 of those at level 55. That same paladin *can* spend ~30AA points to get divine stun, then spend the AAs reducing it from the base 30 second recast to a more reasonable 9 second recast, then spend more AAs getting the &quot;ugrade&quot; to Celestial stun which will allow it to affect level 70 mobs. After that point, he will have 2 chainable stuns (still not enough to chain a mob). <br /> <br />In order for a paladin to actually chain stun a mob at level 70, he must have the normal &quot;force of&quot; line of spells, buy all his stun AAs, and gotten an ancient rune from OoW to get his ancient stun spell. At that point, he can now chain level 70 mobs just as well as he could back when he was level 55. <br /> <br />So yeah. Technically, a paladin can chain stun mobs, but not nearly as easily as they used to be able to, and many paladins will not likely be getting their hands on an ancient rune any time soon. <br /> <br />To give you an equivalent, it would be like making the *only* useable snare or slow spells that could affect level 70 mobs require an ancient rune. If that were the case, you can bet your ass that every single class in that situation would be screaming bloody murder. Having an ability (slowing/snaring) that they could do for the last 20 levels suddenly require a very hard to obtain rune would be seen as destroying the effectiveness of the class. <br /> <br />Yet when this exact thing is done to paladins, not only is it not recognized, but we get people arguing with us that we've not actually had our stun power reduced at all! <br /> <br />Madness I say! ;)</p>
