		   <br /><nobr><span class="notbold">Score</span>: Good [4.02]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=gbaji&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%">
<p><blockquote><b class="sm">Jiggidyjay of the Seven Seas wrote:</b><hr size="1" />W <br />At level 65 the typical bard will have <a href="HTTP://everquest.allakhazam.com/db/spell.html?spell=4112" title="HTTP://everquest.allakhazam.com/db/spell.html?spell=4112" target="akztarg">Call of Muse</a>, which is 15% DD/Dot focus, 30% overhaste, max level 65 (10% reduction each level over cap). Remember that that reduction is based on the person it's focusing/overhasting, not the bard. Some bards, if doing enough GoD, will have Trusik, which is 25% spell focus/30% overhaste.<hr size="1" /></blockquote> <br /> <br />Ok. That's pretty straightforward. The GoD spell is an upgrade to the &quot;normal&quot; spell. It's a bonus for those those take the time to get it. <br /> <br /><blockquote><b class="sm">Quote:</b><hr size="1" />We get our next upgrade at 68, <a href="HTTP://everquest.allakhazam.com/db/spell.html?spell=5380" title="HTTP://everquest.allakhazam.com/db/spell.html?spell=5380" target="akztarg">Yelhun's Mystic Call</a>. It's 15%/30%, max level 70 and is the 3rd rune turn in. So, we've lost 30% effectiveness off of our level 65 song, get the upgrade, and it's the same thing as our level 65 song.<hr size="1" /></blockquote> <br /> <br />Yeah. I agree that that's screwy. But the thinking is that this spell is the upgrade to Call of Muse, not Trusik. So it has the same value as use, but affects higher levels. Screwy IMO, but SOEs spell dev thinks in terms of spell lines and upgrades along those lines and seems to never bother to look at the whole list of spells and the progression players will go through. Annoying, I agree. <br /> <br /><blockquote><b class="sm">Quote:</b><hr size="1" />At 69, we get Eriki's, which is the same as Trusik, 25%/30%, max level 70. Lost 40% of our level 65 songs effectiveness in this case, to get it back to what it was.<hr size="1" /></blockquote> <br /> <br />Ok. Maybe I'm missing something. Where's the 40% reduction? This looks to be identical to Trusik, except it affects level 70s instead of level 65s. So at level 68, you have the exact same ability that you had at level 65. That ability has just been extended 5 ore levels. Unless I'm missing something? <br /> <br /><blockquote><b class="sm">Quote:</b><hr size="1" />Then, care to guess what our level 70 ancient is? Yes, an upgrade to these songs, a 30%/30%, max level 70, yay!<hr size="1" /></blockquote> <br /> <br />Heh. At least your ancient is an actual straight up upgrade in every way. Paladin's ancient spell basically just gives them a third chainable stun (which is required to actually chain stuns btw). Given that we had *four* chainable stuns at level 55, it would be like making your ancient song have 25% less effect, but be the only one that affected level 70 mobs at all. <br /> <br /> <br />Actually, here's a better comparison. Imagine that each of your songs was a single pulse that only lasted 4 seconds and had a recast time of 12 seconds. Thus, in order to provide that song coverage all the time, you must have three of them and continually cast them in sequence. Now imagine that each of those songs had slightly different values of effect, and that SOE then decided to make the higher level &quot;upgrades&quot; linked to the lower ones so that they cannot be cast in a chain together. Imagine further that you only actually got *one* of those three spells in your basic line. In order to get the other two, you had to spend 30AAs for one and get an ancient rune for the other. All of that just to be able to have your spell going continuously. Oh. And imagine that it cost mana to use them, so that you couldn't keep them going all the time even if you had the complete set. <br /> <br />You'd probably be pretty pissed, wouldn't you? Now imagine having people constantly talk about how overpowered that set of songs was and how because of that you don't really need anything when it comes time to &quot;re-envision&quot; the classes. <br /> <br />That's the level of frustration many paladins feel about this. And it's really not that we think our stuns aren't ok as they are. We just get really discouraged when our stuns are treated as though they are an &quot;uber&quot; ability and we should pay a huge handicap price to pay for them. The problem is that they've overdone it in both directions. The've dramtically reduced the power of our stuns *and* they have removed other powers as well *and* they've increased other classes power while leaving ours the same in many areas (like dps and raw tanking ability).</p>
